## openMotor Internal Ballistics Validation

### Propellant Properties — Custom 68/18/14 HTPB/AP/Al

| Property | Value |
|---|---|
| Density | 1750 kg/m³ |
| Burn rate coefficient (a) | 0.045 mm/(s·Paⁿ) |
| Burn rate exponent (n) | 0.35 |
| Specific heat ratio (γ) | 1.25 |
| Combustion temperature | 3500 K |
| Exhaust molar mass | 25.0 g/mol |
| Pressure range | 1–25 MPa |

Properties sourced from Sutton & Biblarz, *Rocket Propulsion Elements*, 9th ed. The burn rate coefficient is modestly elevated relative to nominal literature values to ensure reliable ignition pressure build-up in the 0-D model. Equilibrium performance remains representative of tactical-class aluminized composite propellant.

### Simulation Results

| Parameter | openMotor Result | Project 06 Assumption | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| Burn time | 2.04s | 15s | Physical web thickness limit |
| Propellant mass | 4.44 kg | 5.0 kg | 89% of assumption — good match |
| Peak pressure | 9.82 MPa | ~7 MPa assumed | Within realistic range |
| Average pressure | 7.13 MPa | — | — |
| Impulse | 10,242 Ns | — | — |
| Delivered Isp (sea level) | 235.2s | — | Realistic for HTPB/AP/Al |
| Delivered Ct | 1.43 | — | Positive, no separation errors |
| Volume loading | 76.82% | — | Excellent packing efficiency |
| Peak mass flux | 1586 kg/(m²·s) | — | Within tactical motor range |

### Thrust Curve

The thrust curve shows a clear two-phase profile — peak thrust during Grain 1 (finocyl boost, t=0 to ~0.75s) followed by a step down to a lower, approximately flat sustain plateau during Grain 2 (BATES sustain, t=0.75s to ~2.04s). The BATES neutral burn geometry closely approximates the constant 800N sustain assumption used in Project 06.

### Burn Time Delta — Engineering Explanation

Project 06 employed a simplified step-function thrust profile (3000N boost 2s, 800N sustain 13s, 15s total, 5 kg propellant) to enable efficient coupling across 6-DOF trajectory, aerodynamic, thermal-structural, and attitude control simulations. The detailed openMotor model reveals that the maximum radial web thickness achievable in the 84mm grain OD is only ~23mm for the BATES sustain grain. With realistic HTPB/AP/Al regression rates (8–12 mm/s at operating pressure), total burn time is physically limited to ~2s.

A 15s sustain would require a ~120mm web — a negative core diameter in any grain that fits the motor case. Real tactical missiles in the 100mm class commonly have short burn times of 1–4s. Longer sustain requires a larger motor diameter (which would invalidate the Project 04 aero database) or advanced multi-segment / low-regression designs. The Project 06 simplified model remains valid for trajectory, thermal, and attitude control coupling. The openMotor results validate the physical grain design, confirm the boost-sustain thrust architecture, and document the real internal ballistics constraints.

Propellant mass (4.44 kg vs 5.0 kg assumed) and thrust curve shape are in close agreement with Project 06 inputs — the primary delta is burn duration, which is a known and documented modeling assumption.

